const PHY_OSCILLATIONS = `
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q1</span><span class="pyq-year">2020, 2018, 2011</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>Show that for small oscillations the motion of a simple pendulum is simple harmonic. Derive an expression for its time period. Does it depend on the mass of the bob?</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p><strong>Simple pendulum:</strong> An ideal simple pendulum consists of a point-mass suspended by a flexible, inelastic and weightless string from a rigid support of infinite mass. In practice, we can neither have a point-mass nor a weightless string. In practice, a simple pendulum is obtained by suspending a small metal bob by a long and fine cotton thread from a rigid support.<br/> Expression for time period. In the equilibrium position, the bob of a simple pendulum lies vertically below the point of suspension. If the bob is slightly displaced on either side and released, it begins to oscillate about the mean position.<br/> Suppose at any instant during oscillation, the bob lies at position A when its displacement is O A=x and the thread makes an angle {tex}\\theta{/tex} with the vertical. The forces acting on the bob are<br/> (i) Weight mg of the bob acting vertically downwards.<br/> (ii) Tension T along the string<br/> <img alt="" data-imgur-src="GSVq0XK.png" src="https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/imgur/1685082744-4zx4hp.jpg" style="width: 200px; height: 244px;"/><br/> The force mg has two rectangular components</p> <ol start="1" style="list-style-type: lower-roman;"> <li>the component mg{tex} \\cos \\theta{/tex} acting along the thread is balanced by the tension T in the thread and</li> <li>the tangential component m g{tex}\\sin \\theta{/tex} is the net force acting on the bob and tends to bring it back to the mean position. Thus, the restoring force is</li> </ol> <p>F = {tex}-m g \\sin \\theta=-m g\\left(\\theta-\\frac{\\theta^{3}}{3 !}+\\frac{\\theta^{5}}{5 !}-\\ldots . .\\right){/tex}<br/> {tex}=-m g \\theta\\left(1-\\frac{\\theta^{2}}{6}+\\frac{\\theta^{4}}{120}-\\ldots . .\\right){/tex} <br/> where {tex} \\theta{/tex} is in radians. Clearly, oscillations are not simple harmonic because the restoring force F is not proportional to the angular displacement {tex} \\theta{/tex}.<br/> However, if {tex}\\theta{/tex} is so small that its higher powers can be neglected, then<br/> F = -mg{tex} \\theta{/tex}<br/> If l is the length of the simple pendulum, then<br/> {tex}\\theta(\\mathrm{rad})=\\frac{\\operatorname{arc}}{\\text { radius }}=\\frac{x}{l}{/tex}<br/> {tex}\\therefore{/tex} {tex}F=-m g \\frac{x}{l}{/tex}<br/> or {tex}m a=-\\frac{m g}{l} x{/tex}<br/> or {tex}a=-\\frac{g}{l} x=-\\omega^{2} x{/tex}<br/> Thus, the acceleration of the bob is proportional to its displacement x and is directed opposite to it. Hence for small oscillations, the motion of the bob is simple harmonic. Its time period is<br/> {tex}T=\\frac{2 \\pi}{\\omega}=\\frac{2 \\pi}{\\sqrt{g / l}}{/tex} or {tex}T=2 \\pi \\sqrt{\\frac{l}{g}}{/tex}<br/> Obviously, the time period of a simple pendulum depends on its length l and acceleration due to gravity {tex}\\theta{/tex} but is independent of the mass m of the bob.</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q2</span><span class="pyq-year">2020, 2016, 2015, 2014</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>Find the total energy of the particle executing S.H.M. and show graphically the variation of P.E. and K.E. with time in S.H.M. What is the frequency of these energies with respect to the frequency of the particle executing S.H.M?</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>The total energy of the system of a block and a spring is equal to the sum of the potential energy stored in the spring plus the kinetic energy of the block and is proportional to the square of the amplitude.<br /> {tex}\\frac12{/tex}m{tex}\\omega^2{/tex}(A<sup>2</sup> - x<sup>2</sup>) + {tex}\\frac12{/tex}m{tex}\\omega^2{/tex}x<sup>2</sup><br /> E = {tex}\\frac12{/tex}m{tex}\\omega^2{/tex}A<sup>2</sup><br /> Hence, the total energy of the particle in SHM is constant and it is independent of the instantaneous displacement. Relationship between potential energy, kinetic energy, and time in Simple Harmonic Motion at t = 0, when x = {tex}\\pm{/tex}A.<br /> <img src="https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1708945650-6fkwxs.jpg" style="height:142px; width:150px" /><br /> The frequency of kinetic energy is twice the frequency of SHM.</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q3</span><span class="pyq-year">2020, 2016</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>What is the frequency of oscillation of a simple pendulum mounted in a cabin that is falling freely under gravity?</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>The pendulum is in a state of Weightlessness i.e. g. = 0. The frequency of pendulum is given by ,&nbsp;{tex}\\nu = \\frac { 1 } { 2 \\pi } \\sqrt { \\frac { g } { I } } = 0{/tex}&nbsp;</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q4</span><span class="pyq-year">2020</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><ol start="1" style="list-style-type:lower-roman"> <li>In SHM of a particle, draw graphs showing variation in <ol start="1" style="list-style-type:lower-alpha"> <li>displacement,</li> <li>velocity and</li> <li>acceleration with time. Hence discuss the phase relationship between them using proper equations.</li> </ol> </li> <li>If the following function represents SHM of a particle, find the amplitude of oscillation, {tex}F(t)=(\\sin \\omega t-\\cos \\omega t){/tex} units</li> </ol></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><ol start="1" style="list-style-type:lower-roman"> <li><img src="https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1708945819-8bbjj3.jpg" style="height:334px; width:250px" /><br /> X = A cos {tex}\\omega{/tex}t<br /> {tex}=A \\cos \\left(\\frac{2 \\pi}{T} t\\right)\\left(\\because \\omega=\\frac{2 \\pi}{T}\\right){/tex}<br /> {tex}v=-\\omega A \\sin \\omega t{/tex}<br /> {tex}=-\\omega \\mathrm{A} \\sin \\left(\\frac{2 \\pi}{T} t\\right){/tex}<br /> {tex}a=-\\omega^2 A \\cos \\omega t{/tex}<br /> {tex}=-\\omega^2 A \\cos \\left(\\frac{2 \\pi}{T} t\\right){/tex}</li> <li>{tex}y=\\sin \\omega t-\\cos \\omega t{/tex}<br /> {tex}\\frac{d y}{d t}=\\omega \\cos \\omega t+\\omega \\sin \\omega t{/tex}<br /> {tex}\\frac{d^2 y}{d t^2}=-\\omega^2 \\sin \\omega t+\\omega^2 \\cos \\omega t{/tex}<br /> {tex}=-\\omega^2(\\sin \\omega t-\\cos \\omega t){/tex}.<br /> {tex}a=-\\omega^2 y{/tex}.<br /> {tex}\\therefore a \\propto-y{/tex}.</li> </ol></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q5</span><span class="pyq-year">2019</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>A body oscillates with SHM according to the equation (in SI units),<br /> x = 5 cos [2{tex}\\pi{/tex}t + {tex}\\frac{\\pi}{4}{/tex}].<br /> At t = 1.5 s, calculate the</p> <ol start="1" style="list-style-type: lower-alpha;"> <li>displacement,</li> <li>speed and</li> <li>acceleration of the body</li> </ol></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><ol start="1" style="list-style-type: lower-alpha;"> <li>Equation of SHM is given by , x (t) = 5.0 cos{tex}\\left[ \\ 2 \\pi t + \\pi / 4\\right.]{/tex}&nbsp;m<br /> time, t = 1.5 s<br /> x(t) =&nbsp;{tex}5.0 \\times \\cos [ 2 \\pi \\times 1.5 + \\pi / 4 ]{/tex}&nbsp;|<br /> {tex}= 5.0 \\times \\cos \\left( 3 \\pi + \\frac { \\pi } { 4 } \\right) = - 5.0 \\cos \\frac { \\pi } { 4 }{/tex}&nbsp;<br /> = -5.0 {tex}\\times{/tex}&nbsp;(0.707) = -3.535 m,</li> <li>Now velocity of the particle executing SHM is given by,<br /> {tex}v = \\frac { d x } { d t } = \\frac { d } { d t } \\left[ 5.0 \\cos \\left( 2 \\pi t + \\frac { \\pi } { 4 } \\right) \\right]{/tex}&nbsp;&nbsp;<br /> =&nbsp;{tex} - 5.0 \\times \\sin \\left( 2 \\pi t + \\frac { \\pi } { 4 } \\right) \\times 2 \\pi{/tex}&nbsp;&nbsp;<br /> =&nbsp;{tex} - 10 \\pi \\sin \\left( 2 \\pi t + \\frac { \\pi } { 4 } \\right){/tex}&nbsp;<br /> {tex}\\therefore \\quad \\left. \\frac { d x } { d t } \\right| _ { t = 1.5 s} = - 10 \\pi \\sin \\left( 3 \\pi + \\frac { \\pi } { 4 } \\right)m/s{/tex}{tex}= 10 \\pi \\times 0.707{/tex}&nbsp;m/s<br /> = 22.22 m/s &nbsp;</li> <li>Acceleration of the particle executing SHM&nbsp;is given by<br /> {tex}a = \\frac { d v } { d t } = \\frac { d } { d t } \\left[ - 10 \\pi \\sin \\left[ 2 \\pi t + \\frac { \\pi } { 4 } \\right] \\right]{/tex}&nbsp;<br /> =&nbsp;{tex} - 10 \\pi \\times 2 \\pi \\cos \\left( 2 \\pi t + \\frac { \\pi } { 4 } \\right){/tex}&nbsp;<br /> {tex}\\left. \\frac { d v } { d t } \\right| _ { t = 1.5s } = - 20 \\pi ^ { 2 } \\cos \\left( 3 \\pi + \\frac { \\pi } { 4 } \\right) = 139.56 ~\\mathrm { m } / \\mathrm { s } ^ { 2 }{/tex}</li> </ol></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q6</span><span class="pyq-year">2019</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>Define SHM. What are its characteristics? At what distance from the mean position of amplitude r, the energy is half kinetic and half potential?</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>SHM, is defined as a motion in which the restoring force is directly proportional to the displacement of the body from its mean position.<br /> Characteristics of Simple Harmonic Motion:</p> <ul> <li>The particle&#39;s acceleration in simple harmonic motion is directly proportional to its displacement and directed towards its mean location.</li> <li>The particle&#39;s total energy is preserved as it moves in a simple harmonic motion.</li> <li>SHM is a type of periodic motion</li> </ul> <p>Let the displacement of particle executing S.H.M = Y<br /> Amplitude of particle executing S.H.M = a<br /> Mass of particle = m<br /> Angular velocity = w<br /> The kinetic energy = {tex}\\frac{1}{2} m w^2\\left(a^2-y^2\\right){/tex}<br /> Potential energy = {tex}\\frac{1}{2} m w^2 y^2{/tex}<br /> If kinetic energy = Potential energy<br /> {tex}\\frac{1}{2} m w^2\\left(a^2-y^2\\right)=\\frac{1}{2} m w^2 y^2{/tex}<br /> a<sup>2</sup> - y<sup>2</sup> = y<sup>2</sup><br /> a<sup>2</sup> = 2y<sup>2</sup><br /> {tex}a=\\sqrt{2 y} {/tex}&nbsp;{tex}\\rightarrow{/tex}&nbsp;Square root on both sides<br /> {tex}Y=\\frac{a}{\\sqrt{2}}{/tex}<br /> &nbsp;</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q7</span><span class="pyq-year">2018</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>A block whose mass is 1 kg is fastened to a spring. The spring has a spring constant of 50 Nm<sup>-1</sup>. The block is pulled to a distance x = 10 cm from its equilibrium position at x = 0 on a frictionless surface from rest at t = 0. Calculate the kinetic, potential and total energies of the block when it is 5 cm away from the mean position.</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>Given, mass(m) =1 kg, spring constant(k) =50 Nm<sup>-1</sup>, amplitude(A) =10 cm = 0.1 m, displacement(x) = 5 cm =0.05 m<br /> Kinetic energy,<br /> K =&nbsp;{tex}\\frac { 1 } { 2 } k \\left( A ^ { 2 } - x ^ { 2 } \\right){/tex}<br /> {tex}K = \\frac { 1 } { 2 } \\times 50 \\times \\left[ ( 0.1 ) ^ { 2 } - ( 0.05 ) ^ { 2 } \\right]{/tex}<br /> = 0.1875 J<br /> The potential energy of the block<br /> U =&nbsp;{tex}\\frac { 1 } { 2 } k x ^ { 2 }{/tex}<br /> {tex}= \\frac { 1 } { 2 } \\times 50 \\times ( 0.05 ) ^ { 2 }{/tex}<br /> = 0.0625 J<br /> Total energy, E = K + U = 0.1875 + 0.0625<br /> E =0.25 J<br /> &nbsp;</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q8</span><span class="pyq-year">2018</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>A simple pendulum is inside a space craft. What should be its time period of vibration?</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>Inside a spacecraft, g = 0<br /> Therefore,&nbsp;{tex}T=2 \\pi \\sqrt{\\frac{l}{g}}=2 \\pi \\sqrt{\\frac{l}{0}}=\\infty{/tex}</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q9</span><span class="pyq-year">2018</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>Show that the horizontal oscillations of a massless loaded spring are simple harmonic. Deduce an expression for its time period.</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>Horizontal oscillations of a body on a spring. Consider a massless spring lying on a frictionless horizontal table. Its one end is attached to a rigid support and the other end to a body of mass m. If the body is pulled towards right through a small distance x and released, it starts oscillating back and forth about its equilibrium position under the action of the restoring force of elasticity,<br/> F = -kx<br/> where k is the force constant (restoring force per unit compression or extension) of the spring. The negative sign indicates that the force is directed oppositely to x.<br/> <img alt="" data-imgur-src="YHWauBa.png" src="https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/imgur/1685082740-rz7m9a.jpg" style="width: 250px; height: 205px;"/><br/> If {tex}\\frac {d^{2} x} { d t^{2}}{/tex} is the acceleration of the body, then<br/> {tex}m \\frac{d^{2} x}{d t^{2}}=-k x{/tex}<br/> or {tex}\\frac{d^{2} x}{d t^{2}}=-\\frac{k}{m} x=-\\omega^{2} x{/tex}<br/> This shows that the acceleration is proportional to displacement x and acts opposite to it. Hence the body executes simple harmonic motion. Its time period is given by<br/> T = {tex}\\frac{2 \\pi}{\\omega}=\\frac{2 \\pi}{\\sqrt{\\frac k m}}{/tex}<br/> or {tex}T=2 \\pi \\sqrt{\\frac{m}{k}}{/tex}<br/> The frequency of oscillation will be<br/> {tex}v=\\frac{1}{T}=\\frac{1}{2 \\pi} \\sqrt{\\frac{k}{m}}{/tex}<br/> Clearly, the time period T will be small or frequency {tex}\\nu{/tex} large if the spring is stiff (high k) and the attached body is light (small m).</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q10</span><span class="pyq-year">2017</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>A particle is executing SHM of amplitude A. At what displacement from the mean position, is the energy half kinetic and half potential?</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>According to the above problem, E<sub>k</sub> = E<sub>p</sub> [E<sub>k</sub>&nbsp;and E<sub>p</sub> are kinetic and potential energies respectively]<br /> {tex}\\therefore \\quad \\frac { 1 } { 2 } m \\omega ^ { 2 } \\left( A ^ { 2 } - x ^ { 2 } \\right) = \\frac { 1 } { 2 } m \\omega ^ { 2 } x ^ { 2 }{/tex}<br /> {tex}\\Rightarrow{/tex}&nbsp;A<sup>2</sup>&nbsp;- x<sup>2</sup>&nbsp;= x<sup>2</sup>&nbsp;or 2x<sup>2</sup>&nbsp;= A<sup>2</sup><br /> {tex}\\Rightarrow x ^ { 2 } = \\frac { A ^ { 2 } } { 2 } \\text { or } x = \\pm \\frac { A } { \\sqrt { 2 } }{/tex}<br /> Thus, the energy will be half kinetic and half potential at a displacement of x =&nbsp;{tex}\\frac { A } { \\sqrt { 2 } }{/tex}&nbsp;on either side of the mean position.</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q11</span><span class="pyq-year">2017</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>What are the two basic characteristics of a simple harmonic motion?</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>Two basic characteristics of a simple harmonic motion are:</p> <ol start="1" style="list-style-type: lower-roman;"> <li>Acceleration is directly proportional to displacement from mean position, and the direction of acceleration is towards mean position.</li> <li>Restoring force is directly proportional to displacement, the direction of force and displacement are opposite i.e.,&nbsp;{tex}F = - k x{/tex}.</li> </ol></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q12</span><span class="pyq-year">2017</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>A spring having a force constant k is divided into three equal parts. What would be the force constant for each individual part?</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>Force constant of the spring k = {tex}\\frac{F}{x}{/tex}, where F is the restoring force. When the spring is divided into three parts, the displacement for the same force reduces to {tex}\\frac{x}{3}{/tex}, therefore, the force constant for each individual part is<br /> k&#39; =&nbsp;{tex}\\frac{F}{x / 3}=3\\left(\\frac{F}{x}\\right){/tex}&nbsp;= 3k</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q13</span><span class="pyq-year">2016</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>What is meant by simple harmonic motion? Give any two examples. Write its differential form.</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p><strong>Simple harmonic motion:</strong>&nbsp;A particle is said to execute simple harmonic motion if it moves to and fro about a mean position under the action of a restoring force which is directly proportional to its displacement from the mean position and is always directed towards the mean position.<br /> If the displacement of the oscillating body from the mean position is small, then<br /> Restoring force {tex}\\propto{/tex} Displacement<br /> {tex}F \\propto x{/tex}&nbsp;or&nbsp;F = - kx<br /> This equation defines S.H.M. Here k is a positive constant called force constant or spring factor and is defined as the restoring force produced per unit displacement. The SI unit of k is Nm<sup>-1</sup>. The negative sign in the above equation shows that the restoring force F always acts in the opposite direction of the displacement x. Now, according to Newton&#39;s second law of motion,<br /> F = ma<br /> {tex}\\therefore{/tex}&nbsp;ma = -kx<br /> or&nbsp;{tex}a=-\\frac{k}{m} x{/tex}&nbsp; i.e., a&nbsp;{tex}\\propto{/tex}&nbsp;x&nbsp;<br /> Hence simple harmonic motion may also be defined as follows :<br /> A particle is said to possess simple harmonic&nbsp;motion if it moves to and fro about a mean position under an acceleration that is directly proportional to its displacement from the mean position and is always directed towards that position.<br /> Examples of simple harmonic motion:</p> <ol start="1" style="list-style-type: lower-roman;"> <li>Oscillations of a loaded spring.</li> <li>Vibrations of a tuning fork.</li> <li>Vibrations of the balance wheel of a watch.</li> <li>Oscillations of a freely suspended magnet in a uniform magnetic field.</li> </ol> <p>The differential equation for S.H.M. is<br /> {tex}\\frac{d^{2} x}{d t^{2}}+\\omega^{2} x{/tex}&nbsp;= 0</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q14</span><span class="pyq-year">2015</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>Can displacement and acceleration be in the same direction in S.H.M.?</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>No. In S.H.M., acceleration is always in the opposite direction of displacement.</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q15</span><span class="pyq-year">2014, 2006</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>Show that for a particle in linear S.H.M., the average kinetic energy over a period of oscillation is equal to the average potential energy over the same period. At what distance from the mean position is the kinetic energy in simple harmonic oscillator equal to potential energy?</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>Let x = A sin{tex}\\omega{/tex}t<br /> Then, v = {tex}\\frac{dx}{dt}{/tex} = A{tex}\\omega{/tex} cos ({tex}\\omega{/tex}t)<br /> K. E. = {tex}\\frac{1}{2}{/tex}mv<sup>2</sup><br /> Average kinetic energy is<br /> {tex}\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{~T}} \\int_\\limits0^{\\mathrm{T}} \\frac{1}{2} \\mathrm{mv}^2 \\mathrm{dt}{/tex} = {tex}\\frac{1}{4}{/tex}mA<sup>2</sup>{tex}\\omega^2{/tex}<br /> Average potential energy is<br /> {tex}\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{~T}} \\int_\\limits0^{\\mathrm{T}} \\frac{1}{2} \\mathrm{kx}^2 \\mathrm{dt}{/tex} = {tex}\\frac{1}{4}{/tex}mA<sup>2</sup> {tex}\\omega^2 {/tex}<br /> Let x be the distance where KE is equal to PE. Kinetic energy of particles executing SHM is<br /> KE = {tex}\\frac12{/tex}m{tex}\\omega{/tex}<sup>2</sup>(a<sup>2</sup> &minus; x<sup>2</sup>)<br /> Potential energy of particles is given by PE = {tex}\\frac12{/tex}m{tex}\\omega{/tex}<sup>2</sup>x<sup>2</sup> Let x be the distance where KE = PE<br /> {tex}\\frac12{/tex}m{tex}\\omega{/tex}<sup>2</sup>(a<sup>2</sup> &minus; x<sup>2</sup>) = {tex}\\frac12{/tex}m{tex}\\omega{/tex}<sup>2</sup>x<sup>2</sup><br /> (a<sup>2</sup>&minus; x<sup>2</sup>) = x<sup>2</sup><br /> x = {tex}\\frac{a}{\\sqrt{ 2}}{/tex}<br /> Kinetic energy equal to its potential energy at x = {tex}\\frac{a}{\\sqrt{ 2}}{/tex}</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q16</span><span class="pyq-year">2014</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>Show that for a particle in linear SHM the average kinetic energy over a period of oscillation equal&nbsp;the average potential energy over the same period.</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>Suppose a particle of mass m executes SHM of time period T. The displacement of the particle at any instant t is given by the below general equation,<br /> y = A sin{tex}\\omega{/tex}t<br /> Velocity of the particle is given by, v =&nbsp;{tex}\\frac { d y } { d t } = \\omega A \\cos \\omega t{/tex}<br /> Kinetic energy is given by, E<sub>K</sub>&nbsp;=&nbsp;{tex}\\frac { 1 } { 2 } m v ^ { 2 } = \\frac { 1 } { 2 } m \\omega ^ { 2 } A ^ { 2 } \\cos ^ { 2 } \\omega t{/tex}<br /> and Potential energy is given by, E<sub>p</sub>&nbsp;=&nbsp;{tex}\\frac { 1 } { 2 } m \\omega ^ { 2 } y ^ { 2 } = \\frac { 1 } { 2 } m \\omega ^ { 2 } A ^ { 2 } \\sin ^ { 2 } \\omega t{/tex}<br /> Average KE of the particle executing SHM over a complete period of oscillation is given by,<br /> {tex}E _ { k _ { \\mathrm { av } } } = \\frac { 1 } { T } \\int _ { 0 } ^ { T } E _ { k } d t = \\frac { 1 } { T } \\int _ { 0 } ^ { T } \\frac { 1 } { 2 } m \\omega ^ { 2 } A ^ { 2 } \\cos ^ { 2 } \\omega t~ d t{/tex}<br /> {tex}= \\frac { 1 } { 2 T } m \\omega ^ { 2 } A ^ { 2 } \\int _ { 0 } ^ { T } \\frac { ( 1 + \\cos 2 \\omega t ) } { 2 } d t{/tex}<br /> {tex}= \\frac { 1 } { 4 T } m \\omega ^ { 2 } A ^ { 2 } \\left[ t + \\frac { \\sin 2 \\omega t } { 2 \\omega } \\right] _ { 0 } ^ { T }{/tex}<br /> {tex}= \\frac { 1 } { 4 T } m \\omega ^ { 2 } A ^ { 2 } ( T ) = \\frac { 1 } { 4 } m \\omega ^ { 2 } A ^ { 2 }{/tex}..........(i)<br /> Now average PE of the particle executing SHM over a complete period of oscillation is given by,<br /> {tex}E _ { p _ { \\mathrm { pv } } } = \\frac { 1 } { T } \\int _ { 0 } ^ { T } E _ { p } d t = \\frac { 1 } { T } \\int _ { 0 } ^ { T } \\frac { 1 } { 2 } m \\omega ^ { 2 } A ^ { 2 } \\sin ^ { 2 } \\omega t d t{/tex}<br /> {tex}= \\frac { 1 } { 2 T } m \\omega ^ { 2 } A ^ { 2 } \\int _ { 0 } ^ { T } \\frac { ( 1 - \\cos 2 \\omega t ) } { 2 } d t{/tex}<br /> {tex}= \\frac { 1 } { 4 T } m \\omega ^ { 2 } A ^ { 2 } \\left[ t - \\frac { \\sin 2 \\omega t } { 2 \\omega } \\right] _ { 0 } ^ { T }{/tex}<br /> {tex}= \\frac { 1 } { 4 T } m \\omega ^ { 2 } A ^ { 2 } ( T ) = \\frac { 1 } { 4 } m \\omega ^ { 2 } A ^ { 2 }{/tex}...........(ii)<br /> So it is clearly seen from Eqs.(i) and (ii),&nbsp;{tex}E _ { k _ { \\mathrm { av } } } = E _ { p _ { \\mathrm { av } } }{/tex}</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q17</span><span class="pyq-year">2013</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>One end of a U-tube containing mercury is connected to a suction pump and the other end to atmosphere. A small pressure difference is maintained between the two columns. Show that, when the suction pump is removed, the column of mercury in the U-tube executes simple harmonic motion.</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>For calculation of this problem we can proceed in following manner-<br /> Area of cross-section of the U-tube = A<br /> Density of the mercury column = {tex}\\rho{/tex}&nbsp;<br /> Acceleration due to gravity = g<br /> Restoring force, F = Weight of the mercury column of a certain height<br /> F = &ndash;(Volume&nbsp;{tex}\\times{/tex} Density {tex}\\times{/tex}&nbsp;g)<br /> {tex}F = - ( A \\times 2 h \\times \\rho \\times g ) = - 2 { \\rho }{/tex}&nbsp; gh = &ndash;k {tex}\\times {/tex}&nbsp;Displacement in one of the arms (h)<br /> Where, 2h is the height of the mercury column in the two arms k is a constant, given by {tex}k = - \\frac { F } { h } = 2 A \\rho g{/tex}&nbsp;<br /> Time period, {tex}T = 2 \\pi \\sqrt { \\frac { m } { k } } = 2 \\pi \\sqrt { \\frac { m } { 2 A \\rho g } }{/tex}&nbsp;<br /> Where, m is the mass of the mercury column<br /> Let l be the length of the total mercury in the U-tube.<br /> Mass of mercury, m = Volume of mercury {tex}\\times{/tex}&nbsp;Density of mercury<br /> = Al{tex}\\rho{/tex}&nbsp;<br /> {tex}\\therefore \\; T = 2 \\pi \\sqrt { \\frac { m } { 2 A \\rho g } } = 2 \\pi \\sqrt { \\frac { l } { 2 g } }{/tex}&nbsp;<br /> Hence, the mercury column executes simple harmonic motion with time period {tex}2 \\pi \\sqrt { \\frac { l } { 2 g } }{/tex}.</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q18</span><span class="pyq-year">2013</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>Two identical springs of spring constant k are attached to a block of mass m and to fixed supports as shown in figure. Show that when the mass is displaced from its equilibrium position on either side, it executes a simple harmonic motion. Find the period of oscillations.<br/> <img alt="" data-imgur-src="wqIA4Kv.png" src="https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/imgur/wqIA4Kv.png" style="width: 200px; height: 93px;"/></p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>Force exerted by left spring, trying to pull the mass towards the mean position.<br/> i.e. Restoring force of the left spring, F<sub>1</sub> = -kx<br/> <img alt="" data-imgur-src="9HrrAG9.png" src="https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/imgur/9HrrAG9.png" style="width: 200px; height: 90px;"/><br/> Similarly, force exerted by the right spring, trying to push the mass towards the mean position,<br/> Restoring force of the right spring, F<sub>2</sub> = - kx. k is the spring constant of both the springs.<br/> The net force acting on the mass due to both the springs is<br/> F = F<sub>1</sub> + F<sub>2</sub> = - 2kx<br/> Thus, the force acting on the mass is proportional to its displacement x and is directed towards its mean position. Which are the two main features of an SHM. Hence, the motion of the mass m is simple harmonic. Comparing the equation, F = -2kx with general equation of restoring force, F =- k'x.<br/> We have, equivalent force constant k' = 2k.<br/> The time period of oscillation is T ={tex}2 \\pi \\sqrt { \\frac { m } { k ^ { \\prime } } } = 2 \\pi \\sqrt { \\frac { m } { 2 k } }{/tex}</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q19</span><span class="pyq-year">2011</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>Out of the following functions representing motion of a particle which represents SHM</p> <ol start="1" style="list-style-type: lower-roman;"> <li>y =&nbsp;{tex}\\sin \\omega t-\\cos \\omega t{/tex}</li> <li>y =&nbsp;{tex}\\sin ^{3} \\omega t{/tex}</li> <li>y =&nbsp;{tex}5 \\cos \\left(\\frac{3 \\pi}{4}-3 \\omega t\\right){/tex}</li> <li>y =&nbsp;{tex}1+\\omega t+\\omega^{2} t^{2}{/tex}</li> </ol></div><div class="pyq-options"><div class="option"><div class="option-index"> A </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">Only (i)</p></div></div></div><div class="option"><div class="option-index"> B </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">Only (iv) does not represent SHM</p></div></div></div><div class="option correct"><div class="option-index"> C </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">Only (i) and (iii)</p></div></div></div><div class="option"><div class="option-index"> D </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">Only (i) and (ii)</p></div></div></div></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>y =&nbsp;{tex}1+\\omega t+\\omega^{2} t^{2}{/tex} is algebraic function and y =&nbsp;{tex}\\sin ^{3} \\omega t{/tex} is not harmonic being the product of sin {tex}\\omega{/tex}t (thrice). But y =&nbsp;{tex}\\sin \\omega t-\\cos \\omega t{/tex} and y =&nbsp;{tex}5 \\cos \\left(\\frac{3 \\pi}{4}-3 \\omega t\\right){/tex} are simple harmonic functions. Hence y =&nbsp;{tex}\\sin \\omega t-\\cos \\omega t{/tex} and y =&nbsp;{tex}5 \\cos \\left(\\frac{3 \\pi}{4}-3 \\omega t\\right){/tex} represent SHM.</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q20</span><span class="pyq-year">2010</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>The period of oscillation of a mass M suspended from a spring of negligible mass is T. If along with it another mass M is also suspended, the period of oscillation will now be:</p></div><div class="pyq-options"><div class="option"><div class="option-index"> A </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">T</p></div></div></div><div class="option"><div class="option-index"> B </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">{tex}\\frac T {\\sqrt{2}}{/tex}</p></div></div></div><div class="option"><div class="option-index"> C </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">2T</p></div></div></div><div class="option correct"><div class="option-index"> D </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">{tex}\\sqrt2{/tex}T</p></div></div></div></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>As&nbsp;{tex}T \\propto \\sqrt{M}{/tex}<br /> {tex}\\therefore {/tex}&nbsp;{tex}\\frac{T_{2}}{T_{1}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{M+M}{M}} \\Rightarrow T_{2}=\\sqrt{2} T_{1}=\\sqrt{2 T}{/tex}</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q21</span><span class="pyq-year">2009</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>What is the length of a simple pendulum, which ticks seconds?</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>Given, time period(T) = 2s and acceleration due to gravity(g) = 9.8 m/s<sup>2</sup><br /> We know that, T =&nbsp;{tex}2 \\pi \\sqrt { \\frac { L } { g } } = 2 \\pi \\sqrt { \\frac { L } { 9.8 } }{/tex}<br /> {tex}\\Rightarrow 2 ^ { 2 } = 4 \\pi ^ { 2 } \\times \\frac { L } { 9.8 }{/tex}<br /> {tex}\\Rightarrow L = \\frac { 9.8 } { \\pi ^ { 2 } }{/tex}= 0.992 m{tex} \\simeq {/tex}1.0 m</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q22</span><span class="pyq-year">2009</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><ol start="1" style="list-style-type: lower-roman;"> <li>What is meant by simple harmonic motion?</li> <li>At what points is the energy entirely kinetic and entirely potential in SHM?</li> <li>What is the total distance travelled by a body executing SHM in a time equal to its time period, if its amplitude is A?</li> </ol></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><ol start="1" style="list-style-type: lower-roman;"> <li>Simple harmonic motion is defined as the oscillatory motion to and fro about a fixed point (or equilibrium position) in which the acceleration (or the restoring force) is always directly proportional to the displacement from that point and is always directed towards that fixed point.</li> <li>At the mean position, the energy of a particle executing SHM is entirely kinetic and at the extreme position, the energy is entirely potential.</li> <li>A body executing SHM in a time equal to its time period travels through a total distance of 4 A, where A is its amplitude.</li> </ol></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q23</span><span class="pyq-year">2009</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>A simple harmonic motion is represented by x = 10 sin (20t + 0.5)<br /> Write down its amplitude, angular frequency, frequency, time period and initial phase, if displacement is measured in metres and time in seconds.</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>Given x = 10 sin (20t + 0.5)<br /> Standard equation for displacement in SHM is<br /> x = A sin&nbsp;{tex}\\left(\\omega t+\\phi_{0}\\right){/tex}&nbsp;<br /> Comparing the above two equations, we get</p> <ol start="1" style="list-style-type: lower-roman;"> <li>Amplitude, A = 10 m&nbsp;[{tex}\\because{/tex}&nbsp;A and x have same units]</li> <li>Angular frequency,&nbsp;{tex}\\omega{/tex}&nbsp;= 20 rad s<sup>-1</sup>&nbsp;</li> <li>Frequency, v =&nbsp;{tex}\\frac{\\omega}{2 \\pi}=\\frac{20}{2 \\pi}=\\frac{10}{\\pi}{/tex}&nbsp;= 3.18 Hz</li> <li>Time period, T =&nbsp;{tex}\\frac{2 \\pi}{\\omega}=\\frac{2 \\pi}{20}=\\frac{\\pi}{10}{/tex}&nbsp;= 0.314 s</li> <li>Initial phase,&nbsp;{tex}\\phi_{0}{/tex}&nbsp;= 0.5 rad</li> </ol></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q24</span><span class="pyq-year">2008</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>In what time after its motion begins, will a particle oscillating according to the equation, y = 7 sin 0.5 {tex}\\pi{/tex}t, move from the mean position to maximum displacement?</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>Given y = 7 sin 0.5 {tex}\\pi{/tex}t<br /> On comparing with the standard equation,<br /> y = a sin {tex}\\omega{/tex}t, we get: a = 7, {tex}\\omega{/tex} = 0.5 {tex}\\pi{/tex}&nbsp;<br /> Let t be the time taken by the particle in moving from mean position to maximum displacement.<br /> Then 7 = 7 sin 0.5&nbsp;{tex}\\pi{/tex}t or sin 0.5&nbsp;{tex}\\pi{/tex}t = 1 = sin&nbsp;{tex}\\frac{\\pi}{2}{/tex}<br /> {tex}\\therefore{/tex}&nbsp;{tex}0.5 \\pi t=\\frac{\\pi}{2}{/tex}&nbsp;or t =&nbsp;{tex}\\frac{1}{2 \\times 0.5}{/tex} = 1 s</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q25</span><span class="pyq-year">2006</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>Write the displacement equation representing the following conditions obtained in a simple harmonic motion:<br /> Amplitude = 0.01 m, Frequency = 600 Hz, Initial phase = {tex}\\frac{\\pi}{6}{/tex}</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>y = a sin&nbsp;{tex}\\left(2 \\pi v t+\\phi_{0}\\right){/tex}&nbsp;= 0.01 sin&nbsp;{tex}\\left(1200 \\pi t+\\frac{\\pi}{6}\\right){/tex}</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q26</span><span class="pyq-year">2005</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>The circular motion of a particle with constant speed is:</p></div><div class="pyq-options"><div class="option correct"><div class="option-index"> A </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">periodic but not simple harmonic</p></div></div></div><div class="option"><div class="option-index"> B </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">simple harmonic but not periodic</p></div></div></div><div class="option"><div class="option-index"> C </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">periodic and simple harmonic</p></div></div></div><div class="option"><div class="option-index"> D </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">neither periodic nor simple harmonic</p></div></div></div></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>Uniform circular motion is a periodic motion but not simple harmonic.</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q27</span><span class="pyq-year">2004</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>For a particle in SHM, the displacement x&nbsp;of the particle as a function of time t&nbsp;is given as<br /> x = A sin (2&nbsp;{tex}\\pi{/tex}t)<br /> Here x is in cm&nbsp;and t is in seconds.<br /> Let the time taken by the particle to travel from x = 0 to x = {tex}\\frac{A}{2}{/tex} be t<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;and the time taken to travel from x = {tex}\\frac{A}{2}{/tex} to x = A be t<sub>2</sub>. Find&nbsp;{tex}\\frac{t_{1}}{t_{2}}{/tex}.</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>Here x = 0 at t = 0<br /> Also&nbsp;{tex}\\omega=\\frac{2 \\pi}{T}=2 \\pi{/tex}<br /> {tex}\\therefore{/tex}&nbsp;T = 1s<br /> At t = t<sub>1</sub>, x =&nbsp;{tex}\\frac{A}{2}{/tex}. Therefore,<br /> {tex}\\frac{A}{2}=A \\sin \\left(2 \\pi t_{1}\\right){/tex}&nbsp;or&nbsp;{tex}\\frac{1}{2}=\\sin \\left(2 \\pi t_{1}\\right){/tex}&nbsp;<br /> {tex}\\therefore{/tex}&nbsp;{tex}2 \\pi t_{1}=\\frac{\\pi}{6}{/tex}&nbsp;or t<sub>1</sub> =&nbsp;{tex}\\frac{1}{12}{/tex}&nbsp;s<br /> Time taken from x = 0 to x = A is&nbsp;{tex}\\frac{T}{4}=\\frac{1}{4}{/tex}s<br /> or t<sub>1</sub> + t<sub>2</sub> =&nbsp;{tex}\\frac{T}{4}=\\frac{1}{4}{/tex}s<br /> or t<sub>2</sub> =&nbsp;{tex}\\frac{1}{4}-\\frac{1}{12}=\\frac{1}{6} s{/tex}&nbsp;<br /> Hence&nbsp;{tex}\\frac{t_{1}}{t_{2}}=\\frac{1 / 12}{1 / 6}=\\frac{1}{2}{/tex}</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q28</span><span class="pyq-year">2003</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>The time period of mass suspended from a spring is T. If the spring is cut into four equal parts and the same mass is suspended from one of the parts, then the new time period will be:</p></div><div class="pyq-options"><div class="option"><div class="option-index"> A </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">{tex}\\frac T4{/tex}</p></div></div></div><div class="option"><div class="option-index"> B </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">T</p></div></div></div><div class="option correct"><div class="option-index"> C </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">{tex}\\frac T2{/tex}</p></div></div></div><div class="option"><div class="option-index"> D </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">2T</p></div></div></div></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>{tex}T=2 \\pi \\sqrt{\\frac{m}{k}}{/tex},&nbsp;{tex}k=\\frac{F}{x}{/tex}<br /> When the spring is cut into four equal parts,<br /> {tex}k^{\\prime}=\\frac{F}{\\frac x 4}=4\\left(\\frac{F}{x}\\right)=4 k{/tex}<br /> {tex}\\therefore{/tex}&nbsp;{tex}T^{\\prime}=2 \\pi \\sqrt{\\frac{m}{k^{\\prime}}}=2 \\pi \\sqrt{\\frac{m}{4 k}}=\\frac{T}{2}{/tex}</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q29</span><span class="pyq-year">2003</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>Derive an expression for the instantaneous velocity and acceleration of a particle executing S.H.M.</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>The velocity of the particle executing SHM at any instant of time is given by<br /> {tex}\\mathrm{v}=\\mathrm{A} \\omega \\cos \\omega \\mathrm{t}=\\omega \\sqrt{\\mathrm{A}^2-\\mathrm{y}^2}{/tex}<br /> The acceleration of the particle executing SHM is given by<br /> {tex}\\mathrm{a}=\\frac{\\mathrm{dv}}{\\mathrm{dt}}=-\\mathrm{A} \\omega^2 \\sin \\omega \\mathrm{t}=-\\omega^2 \\mathrm{y}{/tex}<br /> where {tex}\\omega{/tex} - angular frequency, A - amplitude, y - displacement of particle from its mean position in time t .</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q30</span><span class="pyq-year">2002</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>What is the basic condition for the motion of a particle to be S.H.M.?</p></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>The motion of a particle will necessarily be simple harmonic if the restoring force acting on it is proportional to its displacement from the mean position i.e., F = - kx.</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q31</span><span class="pyq-year">1997</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>Two SHM&#39;s with same amplitude and time period, when acting together in perpendicular directions with a phase difference of {tex}\\frac \\pi 2{/tex}, give rise to:</p></div><div class="pyq-options"><div class="option"><div class="option-index"> A </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">straight motion</p></div></div></div><div class="option"><div class="option-index"> B </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">elliptical motion</p></div></div></div><div class="option correct"><div class="option-index"> C </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">circular motion</p></div></div></div><div class="option"><div class="option-index"> D </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">non-circular motion</p></div></div></div></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>Let&nbsp;{tex}x=a \\sin \\omega t{/tex}<br /> and&nbsp;{tex}y=a \\sin (\\omega t+\\pi / 2)=a \\cos \\omega t{/tex}<br /> {tex}\\therefore{/tex}&nbsp;{tex}\\frac{x}{y}=\\frac{x}{\\sqrt{a^{2}-x^{2}}}{/tex}<br /> or&nbsp;{tex}\\frac{x}{y}=\\frac{x}{\\sqrt{a^{2}-x^{2}}}{/tex}<br /> or&nbsp;{tex}y^{2}=a^{2}-x^{2}{/tex}&nbsp;or&nbsp;{tex}x^{2}+y^{2}=a^{2}{/tex}<br /> This is the equation of a circle.</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q32</span><span class="pyq-year">1996</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>A linear harmonic oscillator of force constant 2 {tex}\\times{/tex} 10<sup>6</sup> N/m and amplitude 0.01 m has a total mechanical energy of 160 J. Its</p></div><div class="pyq-options"><div class="option"><div class="option-index"> A </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">P.E. is 160 J</p></div></div></div><div class="option"><div class="option-index"> B </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">P.E. is zero</p></div></div></div><div class="option correct"><div class="option-index"> C </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">P.E. is 100 J</p></div></div></div><div class="option"><div class="option-index"> D </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">P.E. is 120 J</p></div></div></div></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>P.E. ={tex}\\frac{1}{2} k x^{2}=\\frac{1}{2} \\times 2 \\times 10^{6} \\times(0.01)^{2}{/tex}&nbsp;= 100 J</p></div></div></div>
<div class="pyq-card"><div class="pyq-header"><span class="q-number">Q33</span><span class="pyq-year">1991</span></div><div class="pyq-question"><p>A second&#39;s pendulum is mounted in a rocket. Its period of oscillation will decrease when rocket is:</p></div><div class="pyq-options"><div class="option"><div class="option-index"> A </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">moving down with uniform acceleration</p></div></div></div><div class="option"><div class="option-index"> B </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">moving around the earth in geostationary orbit</p></div></div></div><div class="option"><div class="option-index"> C </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">moving up with uniform velocity</p></div></div></div><div class="option correct"><div class="option-index"> D </div><div class="option-text"><div><p style="display:inline">moving up with uniform acceleration</p></div></div></div></div><div class="solution-box"><div class="solution-title">Solution</div><div><p>When at rest, T =&nbsp;{tex}2 \\pi \\sqrt{\\frac{l}{g}}{/tex}<br /> When the rocket moves up with uniform acceleration,<br /> {tex}T^{\\prime}=2 \\pi \\sqrt{\\frac{l}{g+a}}{/tex}<br /> Clearly, T&#39; &lt; T</p></div></div></div>
`;

